<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-228-546  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 228 546.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Feb 20 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japan: Japanese language programming advance.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Yazawa, Naoyuki.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Fujitsu Ltd. (product enhancement).andO;Product:   Japanese Mind (Computer program language) (usage).andO;Topic:     Computer industryJapanese LanguageWord Processing SoftwareEnhancementsWord Processing EquipmentNew Product.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>JAPAN: JAPANESE LANGUAGE PROGRAMMING ADVANCE TOKYO, JAPAN, 1990 FEB 9 (NB) --Japan's dedicated word processor hardware, which allow users to createdocuments in the graphic 6,000-character based Japanese language usingEuropean and American- style keyboards, have recently been threatened by theappearance of compact book-sized computers.andM;Seeing the need to keep the Japanese computer-buying public happy, Fujitsuhas given its word processors, the Oasys 30 series, programmability.andP;  StartSystem E03, which starts up MS-DOS Ver.3.1 on the dedicated Oasys wordprocessors, comes with manuals and two 720-kilobyte floppy disks whichcontain the Japanese programming language, Japanese Mind, for the price of18,000 yen or $124.andP;  This easy-to-use software allows users to write programsin Japanese and compile them to machine language, according to Fujitsu.andM;Fujitsu is hoping that the Japanese featured-software will lure more softwaredevelopers to use its flagship personal computer, FMR series, in the future.andM;(Naoyuki Yazawa/19900215/Press Contact: Fujitsu, 03-216-3211)</TEXT></DOC>